TY  - JOUR
T1  - Striving for Self-Verification during Organizational Entry
AU  - Cable, Daniel M.
AU  - Kay, Virginia S.
Y1  - 2011/03/22
PY  - 2011
DA  - 2012/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.0397
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2010.0397
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 360
EP  - 380
VL  - 55
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - ?Self-verification striving? means bringing others to know you for who you really are, which can be difficult during organizational entry. We predict that some individuals place higher value on self-verification striving than others and that these differences affect the organizational entry process. We present results from two samples of 2,673 people from 107 countries to show how self-verification striving is independent from related constructs (i.e., self-disclosure, self-monitoring, core self-evaluations) and is related to the validity of interviewers' evaluations, job seekers' ability to find satisfying work, and supervisors' evaluations of newcomers' performance.
AB  - ?Self-verification striving? means bringing others to know you for who you really are, which can be difficult during organizational entry. We predict that some individuals place higher value on self-verification striving than others and that these differences affect the organizational entry process. We present results from two samples of 2,673 people from 107 countries to show how self-verification striving is independent from related constructs (i.e., self-disclosure, self-monitoring, core self-evaluations) and is related to the validity of interviewers' evaluations, job seekers' ability to find satisfying work, and supervisors' evaluations of newcomers' performance.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2010.0397
